      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks for the suggestions. I can't use Valgrind on this hardware because it's a bare-metal environment with very limited resources.\n\nLooking at the `system_loop` I sent, I suspect the `SensorPacket* incoming` from `sensor_interface.poll()` might be the issue. If `poll()` is allocating a new packet on the heap every time it finds data, but I'm never calling `delete` on it, that would explain why the RAM slowly disappears. \n\nHow should I modify the loop to ensure that the packet is properly managed without introducing more fragmentation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you've caught the slippery goblin in the act! If `poll()` is indeed conjuring up new packets without a proper farewell, you'll want to make sure you have a proper contract with it. Here's how you can modify your `system_loop` to manage the packets more effectively:\n\n```cpp\nvoid system_loop() {\n    SensorPacket* incoming = nullptr;\n    while (system_running) {\n        incoming = sensor_interface.poll();\n        if (incoming) {\n            process_sensor_data(incoming);\n            // Now, you must ensure that incoming is deleted after processing\n            delete incoming;\n            incoming = nullptr; // Prevent dangling pointer by setting it to null\n        }\n        wait_for_next_tick();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBy setting `incoming` to `nullptr` after deleting it, you prevent any accidental use of a freed pointer, which is like leaving a goblin free to cause mischief elsewhere. Also, remember to check if `sensor_interface.poll()` returns a new pointer or a reference to the existing one. If it's the latter, you won't need to delete it, but you'll still need to manage the pointer correctly to avoid memory leaks.",
